  "prompt": "How is India connected to the internet?",
  "response": "India is connected to the internet through various means:\n\n1. International Submarine Cables\n- Multiple undersea fiber optic cables connect India to global internet networks\n- These cables run through the Indian Ocean, connecting to Europe, Middle East, Africa, and Asia\n- Major cable systems include SEA-ME-WE, I-ME-WE, and MENA\n\n2. Internet Service Providers (ISPs)\n- Major providers like Jio, Airtel, BSNL, and Vi provide internet connectivity\n- They use a combination of fiber optic, wireless, and satellite technologies\n\n3. Domestic Backbone Network\n- National Optical Fiber Network (NOFN) provides high-speed internet\n- State-owned telecom infrastructure supports internet connectivity\n\n4. Satellite Connectivity\n- Satellite internet helps reach remote and rural areas\n- Used as a supplementary connection method\n\n5. Internet Exchange Points (IXPs)\n- Multiple IXPs in cities like Mumbai, Delhi, and Chennai facilitate local internet traffic\n- Help reduce latency and improve network efficiency\n\n6. Mobile Networks\n- 4G and 5G networks provide widespread internet access\n- Significant mobile internet penetration, especially in urban and semi-urban areas\n\nThese interconnected systems ensure India's robust internet connectivity nationally and internationally.",
